1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
First of all, whatever update you got on Dylan, what happened to him, and why he could not return to the game?

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:17,000
I have not had an update. Just knowing he went out when he took awkward landing. I guess I don't know if he fell, but that awkward landing.

3
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
I just heard he wasn't coming back. I haven't got an update yet.

4
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:28,000
It seems pretty obvious, but down Fox, then Harper's out. What kind of pressure does that put on the rest of your backcourt in a game like this?

5
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:37,000
A ton. Obviously, this team is as good as anybody at turning you over, so when you're down some of your primary creators and initiators,

6
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:45,000
it causes a little bit of an extra strain, whether that's who to play, what to play, what to run, et cetera, et cetera.

7
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:52,000
We'll just have to be sharper in that area because it's fully loaded against these guys.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Obviously, 27 points off turnovers is not a winning formula.

9
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Mitch, we hadn't talked to you since the announcement about Fox pre-game.

10
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Is that a situation where, like you said before the game, it's going to be the world you're living in now,

11
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,000
but is that a situation where he could have played if you pushed him today?

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Or I guess how serious is that injury?

13
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Honestly, he's just trying to play every day.

14
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:32,000
It's a tough injury that he wouldn't be playing with in the regular season,

15
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:37,000
so he's trying to tough it out and he did that in Minnesota and then had an awkward landing,

16
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:42,000
and so he re-aggravated it, and we just got to make sure that he's in a place

17
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,000
that he can be out there and compete to the level that he would need to in the game that we're playing.

18
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:53,000
And then I guess as a corollary to those two questions, Steph has been going through some turnover issues.

19
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:58,000
What can you do to kind of address that?

20
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:05,000
We've addressed it and will continue to just in terms of trying to help him with some of his reads,

21
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:11,000
especially when he's tired, whether that's playing more off two feet or getting off the ball earlier with the early pass

22
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,000
and just letting the ball find the open man. They do such a great job of showing crowds

23
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
and the pain having multiple bodies, and so it's not just Steph.

24
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
He had too many turnovers, but our whole team did.

25
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:27,000
And so we have to continue to not fight that moment of the game where they're going to make you pass the ball at times.

26
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:32,000
And when you have those situations, you've got to be able to connect with your teammate

27
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:37,000
because if you do, you go from playing in the crowd to then more than likely getting one of your teammates

28
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:43,000
to the basketball with an advantageous opportunity in terms of close out or catch shot threes.

29
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Even with the turnovers for Steph tonight, what did you think of his performance

30
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:54,000
and the way he was able to play through the circumstances and the physicality that the Thunder played with tonight?

31
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Yeah, he's a warrior. He's out there giving it all he's got.

32
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
I think that when he doesn't pass the ball earlier, he misses a teammate.

33
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
It's out of him being competitive and trying to make a play and be aggressive,

34
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:13,000
and there's a lot of things going on, and he's shown that in the two years that he's been with us,

35
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:18,000
he's a hell of a passer and a hell of a creator, and we've got to continue to help him.

36
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:24,000
He's asked to guard on one end and then create that much, especially without Fox and then Harper.

37
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,000
That's quite an output, energy-wise, and so it's something that he'll be better at

38
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:34,000
and we'll be better for him to try to help him where we don't have to put maybe that much strain on him.

39
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:39,000
Mitch, you got guys on both sides already banged up, going down, leaving the floor.

40
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:43,000
How much of this, after two games, do you feel like is going to be a war of attrition

41
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,000
just with the two teams, the way they play and just how tight everything seems to be?

42
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Yeah, it feels like that's always at this time of the season in every sport, right?

43
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:00,000
You have to get to the end to give yourself a chance, and I think, again,

44
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,000
that's why we have to continue to trust our depth and guys have to step up

45
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,000
and when their names call to answer the bell and be able to give us some quality minutes

46
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:17,000
and then as you do get tired and the physicality heightens and the intensity

47
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:22,000
is ever so present, you got to execute and so there's something there

48
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:31,000
where there's a mental, a physical and emotional challenge, I guess you could say,

49
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
and you have to be able to do that in the micro every possession

50
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
and then in the macro in terms of the totality of how you have a disposition

51
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:42,000
and work a game for 48 minutes.

52
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
On that note, Coach, what did you see from Jordan tonight

53
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
in the way that he was kind of thrown into the fire?

54
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
You mentioned just giving good minutes and spurts wherever you can.

55
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Yeah, Jordan's done that for us all year.

56
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,000
He's done a great job of being ready when his name's called.

57
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:59,000
Very smart basketball player, knows how to execute and give us toughness

58
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
and he was great for us tonight.

